   =20
 =20

The=C2=A0economics of a Paramount Global acquisition are simple but tricky:
=09Paramount has about 655 million shares outstanding.=09Of those 655 milli=
on shares, roughly 41 million are Class A shares, which have voting rights;=
 the rest are Class B shares, which don=E2=80=99t.=09The Class A stock trad=
es at=C2=A0$22.37 per share as of=C2=A0Friday=E2=80=99s close; the Class B =
trades at $11.91. That gives you a combined equity market capitalization of=
 about $8.2 billion.=09Figure you=E2=80=99d have to pay a premium to buy th=
e whole company. Let=E2=80=99s say the total equity value would be $12 bill=
ion, roughly a 50% premium to the current price.
  [1]

=09But notice that=C2=A0you could take over the company =E2=80=94=C2=A0cont=
rol the shareholder vote, elect new directors, vote for a merger, etc. =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0with just 21 million Class A shares. That would represent a maj=
ority of the Class A voting shares, but only about 3.2% of the total shares=
.=09In fact, 31.5 million Class A shares are owned by National Amusements, =
a company controlled by Shari Redstone, the daughter and successor of forme=
r Paramount mogul Sumner Redstone. Those shares represent about 77% of the =
voting stock, but less than 5% of the total stock.
  [2]

=09If you want to acquire Paramount, how much should you offer to pay for R=
edstone=E2=80=99s Class A stock? For the other Class A stock? For the Class=
 B stock?

Assume that you are willing to pay $12 billion of total equity value for th=
e company, and that you will be compelled by competitive pressures to pay t=
hat amount. Two=C2=A0possible answers suggest themselves:
=09The=C2=A0fairest=C2=A0answer is that if you are willing to pay $12 billi=
on for the equity, you should pay about $18.32 per share,
  [3]
=C2=A0treating the A and B shares the same, since they have the same econom=
ic rights.
  [4]
=C2=A0This represents about a 54% premium to the trading price of the Class=
 B shares, but about an 18%=C2=A0discount=C2=A0to the trading price of the =
Class A shares.=09The=C2=A0least fair=C2=A0answer is that if you are willin=
g to pay $12 billion for the equity, you should pay=C2=A0all=C2=A0of it to =
Shari Redstone, because her voting stock is enough to control the company. =
Pay her $380.95 per share for her Class A shares,
  [5]
=C2=A0give everyone else zero, boom, you control the company. She gets abou=
t a 1,600% premium to the last trade; everyone else gets a 100% discount.

Neither of those answers is really feasible: You=E2=80=99re not going to ge=
t the Class A holders to vote to sell their shares at a discount, and if yo=
u announce a plan to buy Redstone=E2=80=99s shares and stiff everyone else,=
 Paramount=E2=80=99s board =E2=80=94=C2=A0which has fiduciary duties to all=
 shareholders =E2=80=94 will try to stop you.=C2=A0(The board of Paramount=
=E2=80=99s predecessor=C2=A0once tried to=C2=A0take away=C2=A0Redstone=E2=
=80=99s votes, arguing that was in the best interests of other shareholders=
.) And if you just buy Redstone=E2=80=99s shares, take control and leave th=
e Class B and minority Class A shares outstanding, they will=C2=A0stick aro=
und and make various sorts of economic and legal trouble.
  [6]

But those are the boundaries, and then you have to find the right place on =
the curve between them. You have to give Redstone enough for her shares to =
make it worth her while, and you have to give everyone else enough that the=
 board will let you do it. And, in a competitive auction, different bidders=
 might strike the balance in different ways; Redstone might end up favoring=
 the more Redstone-friendly bidder, while the board might end up favoring t=
he more Class B-friendly one.
We talk sometimes about my simple model of distressed debt investing: If yo=
u=E2=80=99re a company with $100 of debt outstanding, you go to the holders=
 of 51% of it and say =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll pay you back 105 cents on the =
dollar if you vote to stiff the other guys.=E2=80=9D So you pay $53.55 to t=
he majority and $0 to the minority and come out ahead. That doesn=E2=80=99t=
=C2=A0really=C2=A0work, but it=E2=80=99s the schematic intuition behind lot=
s of other things (=E2=80=9Cnon-pro rata uptiering,=E2=80=9D etc.) that do =
work.
We also talk sometimes about how it=E2=80=99s harder to pull off this sort =
of thing in=C2=A0equity=C2=A0deals (like mergers): Getting 51% of bondholde=
rs to vote to stiff the other 49% is endlessly popular, but getting 51% of=
=C2=A0shareholders=C2=A0to vote to stiff the other 49% is not really allowe=
d; there are fiduciary duties and protections and expectations that all sha=
reholders will get treated fairly.=C2=A0
On the other hand, at Paramount you can control of 100% of the company by b=
uying 5% of the stock. Of course that is a temptation.
The Wall Street Journal checks in on Paramount=E2=80=99s deal talks:

When David Ellison, the CEO of production company Skydance Media and son of=
 billionaire Larry Ellison, raised the idea of a merger, [Shari] Redstone w=
as ready to hand over a media empire her family has controlled for nearly f=
our decades. =E2=80=A6
Paramount has been in exclusive talks with Skydance toward a deal that woul=
d net Redstone more than $2 billion in cash for National Amusements, the ho=
lding company that owns the family=E2=80=99s 77% voting stake in Paramount =
and a chain of movie theaters. Nonvoting Paramount investors would get stoc=
k in a newly merged company.=C2=A0
The current value of Redstone=E2=80=99s Paramount holding is about $750 mil=
lion, meaning she would be getting a substantial premium in a Skydance deal=
.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6
An independent board committee has been tasked with reviewing the Skydance =
deal. In a statement, National Amusements said it would respect the committ=
ee=E2=80=99s decision on =E2=80=9Cwhether the Skydance deal presents an att=
ractive transaction for Paramount and whether they want to continue to move=
 forward.=E2=80=9D National Amusements has signaled that it is open to maki=
ng a transaction contingent on approval by a majority of non-Redstone share=
holders, people close to the talks said.=C2=A0
Paramount has another potential option on the table. Private-equity giant A=
pollo Global Management submitted a $26 billion offer, including about $12 =
billion in equity plus assumption of debt. =E2=80=A6 An Apollo deal could b=
e much more appealing to Paramount shareholders=E2=80=94giving them a cash =
payout=E2=80=94but wouldn=E2=80=99t give Redstone the hefty premium Skydanc=
e is offering.

The proposed Skydance deal involves (1) paying Redstone cash for National A=
musements (and, thus, the controlling block of Class A shares) and (2)=C2=
=A0not=C2=A0paying cash for the rest of the non-controlling shares:

The deal itself would be structured in two steps. First, Skydance, which is=
 backed by the Ellison family, and private-equity firms KKR and RedBird Cap=
ital Partners, would buy out National Amusements. Then, Paramount would acq=
uire Skydance with stock at a valuation of $5 billion.
The valuation has turned heads since the Journal first reported on Skydance=
=E2=80=99s financials. The company=E2=80=99s expected revenue this year of =
just over $1 billion is one-thirtieth of Paramount=E2=80=99s and it is expe=
cted to generate earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortiza=
tion of $90 million.

Right I mean there is some economic pie to be divided up here, and 95% of t=
he shares have no voting power. If you make a good deal with the person who=
 owns the controlling 5%, you can get a good deal for yourself too.

