   =20
      Freedom of speech
   =20
 =20

As a matter of US constitutional law, the argument =E2=80=9CI should be all=
owed to commit securities fraud because of freedom of speech and the First =
Amendment=E2=80=9D is=C2=A0wrong,=C2=A0but it has a respectable intellectua=
l pedigree. You can see its appeal. The US Securities and Exchange Commissi=
on does=C2=A0pretty intrusively regulate speech, in a way that would not be=
 acceptable in most areas of US law. And if the First Amendment protects an=
ything, it protects the right to lie to the public. But not about securitie=
s.
On the other hand, the composition of the US courts is changing;=C2=A0they =
are becoming more skeptical of regulatory agencies=C2=A0and more receptive =
to arguments that regulatory restrictions on freedom are unconstitutional. =
It=E2=80=99s worth trying, every now and then, to see if the US Supreme Cou=
rt might change its mind and decide that, actually, freedom of speech=C2=A0=
does=C2=A0require the right to commit securities fraud.
Not today though:

The US Supreme Court rejected an appeal from Elon Musk in his =E2=80=9CTwit=
ter sitter=E2=80=9D case, leaving intact his agreement with the Securities =
and Exchange Commission to have an in-house lawyer pre-approve his social m=
edia posts about Tesla Inc.
The justices, without comment, refused to hear contentions from the Tesla c=
hief executive officer that the accord he signed in 2018 now violates his c=
onstitutional free speech rights.
Musk has battled the SEC over his social media posts since he tweeted in Au=
gust 2018 that he had =E2=80=9Cfunding secured=E2=80=9D to take Tesla priva=
te, sending shares of the electric carmaker surging.
The regulator claimed in a lawsuit the following month that Musk misled sha=
reholders with that post. Two days later, Musk settled with the SEC, agreei=
ng to resign as Tesla chairman and pay $20 million as part of the deal. =E2=
=80=A6
The agreement is a =E2=80=9Cquintessential prior restraint that the law for=
bids,=E2=80=9D Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers argued in the Supreme Court appeal. =
=E2=80=9CThe pre-approval provision at issue continues to cast an unconstit=
utional chill over Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s speech whenever he considers making p=
ublic communications.=E2=80=9D

They are not=C2=A0exactly=C2=A0wrong, but they are wrong enough. The SEC re=
ally is in the business of chilling Elon Musk from saying stuff about Tesla=
=E2=80=99s stock, and that=E2=80=99s fine.

 =20
   =20
      Low rates phenomena
   =20
 =20

One straightforward story you could tell about recent financial history is =
that interest rates were low for a very long time, which meant=C2=A0that di=
scount rates were low, which meant that a dollar in the distant future was =
pretty much as good as a dollar right now, which meant that investors were =
willing to put their money into risky bets with no expectation of any cash =
flows anytime soon. Thus a huge boom in the valuations of speculative priva=
te tech companies. Thus the =E2=80=9C
MoviePass economy,=E2=80=9D where venture capitalists were willing to inves=
t billions in companies that lost money on every transaction, in the hope t=
hat one day those companies would achieve enough scale to stop doing that. =
And thus crypto, where markets gave huge valuations to speculative tokens w=
ithout even a plan to one day have cash flows.
And then rates went up and that all evaporated. At the Wall Street Journal,=
 James Mackintosh wrote yesterday that now =E2=80=9Cinvestors want a clear =
route to a return on corporate cash sunk into new projects,=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9Cmoney that flooded into risky ventures that won=E2=80=99t pay divi=
dends for years, if ever, was much more acceptable when interest rates were=
 near zero than when the alternative is a Treasury yielding almost 5%.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0
This strikes me as basically a correct story, but artificial intelligence s=
pending=C2=A0is maybe an exception? The Journal also reports:

Despite a broad downturn in the startup sector, investors chasing the stock=
 market successes of Nvidia and Microsoft have deluged AI upstarts with rec=
ord levels of funding, minting dozens of companies with billion-dollar valu=
ations in the past year. The investment frenzy is already fueling concerns =
of a bubble as startups struggle to translate the hype into revenue.
=E2=80=9CEveryone believes that AI is the future, so we are going to see an=
 extraordinary amount of investment until proven otherwise,=E2=80=9D said A=
lex Clayton, a general partner at the venture firm Meritech. =E2=80=9CThe p=
roblem is that we don=E2=80=99t know what these business models are going t=
o look like at scale. You can have theories about it, but you really don=E2=
=80=99t know.=E2=80=9D
Fears of rising startup valuations aren=E2=80=99t new in Silicon Valley. Bu=
t the AI gold rush is notable because investors are writing massive checks=
=E2=80=94sometimes in the hundreds of millions of dollars=E2=80=94just to g=
et these companies off the ground. Even during the peak of the startup boom=
, such large financings were reserved for later-stage private companies gea=
ring up for aggressive growth. =E2=80=A6
Imbue hit a valuation of more than $1 billion with its fundraising last yea=
r, courting backers like Nvidia and ex-Google CEO Eric Schmidt. Chief Execu=
tive Kanjun Qiu dazzled investors with a vision to build intelligent comput=
ers that could give humans the =E2=80=9Cfreedom, dignity, and agency to do =
the things we love.=E2=80=9D Last November, she lavished her employees with=
 a company off-site to Japan.
Imbue is plowing its cash into developing AI models that it hopes will one =
day create autonomous AI agents. A company spokesperson said it made a =E2=
=80=9Cdeliberate strategic decision=E2=80=9D not to commercialize in order =
to focus on research and that investors were on board with this approach.=
=C2=A0

One model of this is =E2=80=9Cartificial general intelligence (AGI) will be=
 so enormously lucrative, and so soon, that your business plans and=C2=A0di=
scount rate don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0matter all that much.=E2=80=9D Sometimes, th=
ough, I think about OpenAI=E2=80=99s great warning to potential investors t=
hat =E2=80=9Cit would be wise to view any investment in OpenAI Global, LLC =
in the spirit of a donation, with the understanding that it may be difficul=
t to know what role money will play in a post-AGI world.=E2=80=9D If your d=
iscounted cash flow model is, like, =E2=80=9CYear 1: spend $1 billion, Year=
 2: spend $2 billion, Year 3: a paradise of universal abundance in which mo=
ney no longer has uses,=E2=80=9D maybe that just breaks Excel?
Also crypto is pretty back, so there=E2=80=99s that.

 =20
   =20
      Republic First
   =20
 =20

One funny feature of financial markets is that sometimes something good or =
bad happens to a company, and the stock of a different company with a simil=
ar name goes up or down. Elon Musk tweets =E2=80=9CUse Signal=E2=80=9D and =
the (unrelated) stock of Signal Advance Inc. goes up, Zoom Video Communicat=
ions Inc. has a popular product and the (unrelated) stock of Zoom Technolog=
ies Inc. goes up, that sort of thing. People are busy and=C2=A0markets are =
slightly less than perfectly efficient.
With banks this is arguably less funny, for two reasons:
=09A bank is a much more reflexive thing than most companies: When people l=
ose confidence in a bank, they don=E2=80=99t just sell the stock; they with=
draw deposits and can cause the bank to fail.=09As I once half-joked on Twi=
tter, there are 4,000 banks in the US and they all have like six names.

The result is that any time a bank announces bad news, 20 other banks get n=
ervous calls from depositors. We talked last year about the time (1) First =
Republic Bank failed and (2) Republic First Bancorp put out a nervous state=
ment to the effect of =E2=80=9Cthat wasn=E2=80=99t us.=E2=80=9D Welp! Bloom=
berg=E2=80=99s Bre Bradham reports:

Republic First Bank became the latest smaller lender to succumb to pressure=
s of higher interest rates on Friday when it was closed by regulators =E2=
=80=94 with most of its deposits and assets acquired by Fulton Bank.
The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said in a statement that Republic First=
=E2=80=99s 32 locations in New Jersey, Pennsylvania and New York will reope=
n Saturday as branches of Fulton Bank. Republic First =E2=80=94 which does =
business as Republic Bank =E2=80=94 had about $6 billion of assets and $4 b=
illion of deposits at the end of January.
The Philadelphia-based bank had struggled with similar issues as other regi=
onal lenders: high interest rates that translated into unrealized losses on=
 loans and securities, leading to the collapse last year of Silicon Valley =
Bank, Signature Bank and First Republic.

I don=E2=80=99t actually think the name thing had that much to do with it, =
but I guess other First banks and other Republic banks should watch out.=C2=
=A0Some banks are systemically important, but other clusters of bank names=
=C2=A0might be systemically important.=C2=A0

