   =20
      24/7
   =20
 =20

Last week, the Financial Times reported=C2=A0that the New York Stock Exchan=
ge =E2=80=9Cis polling market participants on the merits of trading stocks =
around the clock as regulators scrutinise an application for the first 24/7=
 bourse.=E2=80=9D I=C2=A0have often argued that the stock market should be =
open only half an hour a day, not the current 6.5, never mind 24. A reader =
emailed to propose the extreme version of this:
I prefer infrequent=C2=A0batch auctions. The buyside loses to VWAP by like =
2+ bps in aggregate.
  [7]
 If you just had one single-price auction per day, no one would lose to VWA=
P, and intermediation would go down 90%. Could probably run the entire US m=
arket on 1 rack and repurpose those servers and quants to AGI or fusion. So=
mething useful.
The problem of the stock market is that some people want to buy stock, and =
other people want to sell stock, but they don=E2=80=99t all show up at exac=
tly the same moment. If a seller shows up one minute and a buyer the next, =
somebody =E2=80=94=C2=A0a high-frequency market maker =E2=80=94=C2=A0will s=
tep in to buy from the seller, wait, and sell to the buyer. The market make=
r will charge a bit of money for that, and will build algorithms to do it; =
the investors will build their own algorithms to try to save on those costs=
. But if there was exactly one auction per day, then everyone who wanted to=
 buy would just buy from everyone who wanted to sell, pushing down the cost=
 of intermediation and making everything a bit simpler.
Moving to 24/7 trading is of course the opposite of that. But while there i=
s pressure to move to all-night trading, there is=C2=A0also=C2=A0pressure t=
o move to one auction. Sort of. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Justina Lee reports tod=
ay:

The regular market for US equities runs for 390 minutes on a standard tradi=
ng day. But at the rate things are going, eventually the last 10 might be t=
he only ones that matter.
About a third of all S&P 500 stock trades are now executed in the final 10 =
minutes of the session, according to data compiled by BestEx Research, a de=
veloper of trading algorithms. That=E2=80=99s up from 27% in 2021.

But there are objections:

Now fresh evidence emerging from Europe =E2=80=94 where the pattern is simi=
lar =E2=80=94 suggests the trend may be hurting liquidity and distorting pr=
ices.
It=E2=80=99s new ammo for critics of the global boom in passive investing, =
because index funds drive the phenomenon. These products typically buy and =
sell shares at the close, since the last prices of the day are used to set =
the benchmarks they aim to replicate. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CThe common knowledge is that closing auctions are very, very good =
mechanisms to close markets,=E2=80=9D said Benjamin Clapham at Goethe Unive=
rsity Frankfurt, co-author of a new research paper titled Shifting Volumes =
to the Close: Consequences for Price Discovery and Market Quality. =E2=80=
=9CThis might be true, but if we have such a shift of volumes to this very =
last opportunity of trading in the day, we might see price inefficiencies.=
=E2=80=9D
The paper, which Clapham wrote with colleague Micha Bender and Deutsche Bun=
desbank researcher Benedikt Schwemmlein, focused on large-caps on the Londo=
n, Paris and Frankfurt exchanges in the four years through mid-2023. The tr=
io found shares generally move between the end of continuous trading and th=
e last price set in the closing auction, yet 14% of that move reverses over=
night =E2=80=94 a sign it=E2=80=99s fueled by one-sided flows rather than f=
undamentals.

Yeah but pretty much every price move during continuous trading is fueled b=
y one-sided flows. That=E2=80=99s what continuous trading is: It=E2=80=99s =
buyers buying from market makers and sellers selling to market makers, with=
 the market makers continuously taking the other side of one-sided orders. =
If you mush all the buyers and sellers together at once, you probably get a=
 bit less of that.

