xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">that</a> =
the stock market should be open only half an hour a day, not the current 6.=
5, never mind 24. A reader emailed to propose the extreme version of this:<=
/p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I prefer <em>infrequent</em>=C2=A0=
batch auctions. The buyside loses to VWAP by like 2+ bps in aggregate.<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a> If you just had one single-price auction per day, no one would lose to=
 VWAP, and intermediation would go down 90%. Could probably run the entire =
US market on 1 rack and repurpose those servers and quants to AGI or fusion=
. Something useful.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/35199213.256350/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMjUvbnlzZS1mb3Jnb3QtdG8tb3Blbi15ZXN0ZXJkYXk_Y21waWQ=
9QkJEMDQyOTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZX=
R0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNDI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cBc09e8225" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">problem of the stock market</a> is that some peo=
ple want to buy stock, and other people want to sell stock, but they don=E2=
=80=99t all show up at exactly the same moment. If a seller shows up one mi=
nute and a buyer the next, somebody =E2=80=94=C2=A0a high-frequency market =
maker =E2=80=94=C2=A0will step in to buy from the seller, wait, and sell to=
 the buyer. The market maker will charge a bit of money for that, and will =
build algorithms to do it; the investors will build their own algorithms to=
 try to save on those costs. But if there was exactly one auction per day, =
then everyone who wanted to buy would just buy from everyone who wanted to =
sell, pushing down the cost of intermediation and making everything a bit s=
impler.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Moving to 24/7 trading is of course the opposi=
te of that. But while there is pressure to move to all-night trading, there=
 is=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>pressure to move to one auction. Sort of. Bloom=
berg=E2=80=99s Justina Lee <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/35199213.256350/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbG=
VzLzIwMjQtMDQtMjkvc3RvY2tzLXRyYWRlLWZvci0zOTAtbWludXRlcy1hLWRheS1pbmNyZWFza=
W5nbHktb25seS0xMC1tYXR0ZXI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQyOTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1=
bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNDI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWl=
nbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd1df66db" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">reports today<=
/a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The regular market for US equities runs for 39=
0 minutes on a standard trading day. But at the rate things are going, even=
tually the last 10 might be the only ones that matter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">About a third of all S&amp;P 500 stock trades =
are now executed in the final 10 minutes of the session, according to data =
compiled by BestEx Research, a developer of trading algorithms. That=E2=80=
=99s up from 27% in 2021.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there are objections:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now fresh evidence emerging from Europe =E2=80=
=94 where the pattern is similar =E2=80=94 suggests the trend may be hurtin=
g liquidity and distorting prices.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s new ammo for critics of the globa=
l boom in passive investing, because index funds drive the phenomenon. Thes=
e products typically buy and sell shares at the close, since the last price=
s of the day are used to set the benchmarks they aim to replicate. =E2=80=
=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe common knowledge is that closing =
auctions are very, very good mechanisms to close markets,=E2=80=9D said Ben=
jamin Clapham at Goethe University Frankfurt, co-author of a new research p=
aper titled Shifting Volumes to the Close: Consequences for Price Discovery=
 and Market Quality. =E2=80=9CThis might be true, but if we have such a shi=
ft of volumes to this very last opportunity of trading in the day, we might=
 see price inefficiencies.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The paper, which Clapham wrote with colleague =
Micha Bender and Deutsche Bundesbank researcher Benedikt Schwemmlein, focus=
ed on large-caps on the London, Paris and Frankfurt exchanges in the four y=
ears through mid-2023. The trio found shares generally move between the end=
 of continuous trading and the last price set in the closing auction, yet 1=
4% of that move reverses overnight =E2=80=94 a sign it=E2=80=99s fueled by =
one-sided flows rather than fundamentals.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah but pretty much every price move during c=
ontinuous trading is fueled by one-sided flows. That=E2=80=99s what continu=
ous trading <em>is</em>: It=E2=80=99s buyers buying from market makers and =
sellers selling to market makers, with the market makers continuously takin=
g the other side of one-sided orders. If you mush all the buyers and seller=
s together at once, you probably get a bit less of that.</p>
